1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O (7. Qe2 {[%cal Ye1c1,Ye4g5] White delays the short castle, and sometimes may consider the long castle or some ideas connected to Neg5.} Ngf6 8. Neg5 {This is White's most concrete and popular move.} (8. Ng3 {We can continue with the typical idea} Bxf3 $1 9. Qxf3 c5 $1 {which was tried only once in the game Lobanov-Kacharava.}) 8... Qe7 {[%csl Re7,Rg5][%cal Ge8c8] I prefer Qe7 over h6 because we need to remember less forced variations. Our idea is to play 000. The queen on e7 looks strange with the bishop on f8, but White's knight on g5 is also misplaced.} (8... h6 $5 {is also possible, but more risky:} 9. Nxe6 fxe6 10. Bg6+ (10. Qxe6+ $2 Qe7 $19) 10... Ke7 {[%csl Re7] it might not be easy to play with the king on e7, but objectively the position is equal.}) 9. O-O (9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 $36 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Ge8c8,Gd7c5,Yc5d3] 000 and Nc5 next. The engine already slightly prefers Black.}) 9... h6 $1 {it's very important to play h6 right now.} (9... O-O-O $2 {would be a mistake because of} 10. b4 $1 h6 {and White can play} 11. b5 $1 Bd5 12. c4 hxg5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg5 $16) 10. Ne4 Bxe4 11. Bxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 O-O-O $132 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gf8g7] we want to play g5-Bg7 next. We have solved all the opening problems.}) 7... Ngf6 8. Ng3 {White's mainline, by far. 8.Ng3 has been played in around 50% of games that have reached this position.} (8. Nxf6+ {hamrless move, but it has been played more than 600 times.} Qxf6 $1 {[%csl Cf3][%cal Gc6f3] the correct recapture.} 9. Be2 {necessary move to defend f3.} Bd6 10. c4 {[%cal Gd4d5] Critical move. White's idea is d5.} Be4 {[%cal Ge4g6] Known idea. We will rotate our bishop on g6, in real Caro-Kann spirit.}) (8. Neg5 {Concrete move. It's objectively not great for White, but Black needs to know the right reactions.} Bd6 $1 {the right development against 8.Neg5.} (8... Be7 $4 {would be a huge blunder because of} 9. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 10. Ng5+) 9. Re1 (9. Nxf7 $2 {doesn't work now because of} Kxf7 10. Ng5+ Ke7 11. Re1 Nf8 $19 {[%cal Gh7h6] h6 next, and our position is winning.}) 9... h6 $1 {only move, otherwise our position is lost.} 10. Nh3 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf3e5]} (10. Nxe6 $2 fxe6 11. Bg6+ Ke7 {[%cal Gd7f8] Nf8 next.}) (10. Rxe6+ $5 {this amazing move, is actually possible.} Kf8 $1 {critical move.} (10... fxe6 11. Nxe6 Qc8 12. Nxg7+ Kf7 13. Nf5) 11. Rxd6 {only move.} cxd6 12. Nh3 g5 $1 $15 {White has some compensation, but objectively our position is slightly better.}) 10... Bxf3 $1 {necessary move. White will have two bishops, but the knight on h3 is misplaced, and we can create a fast counterplay with c7-c5.} (10... O-O $4 {huge mistake because of} 11. Ne5 $1 $16 {You should always be careful about allowing the Ne5 idea.}) 11. Qxf3 O-O $5 {[%cal Gc7c5] My recommendation. The idea is to play c7-c5 in one move.} (11... c6 {has been an almost automatic move so far. It's also possible, but also White can play. For example:} 12. Nf4) 12. Qxb7 $6 c5 $44 {Full compensation, we have already seen this idea.}) (8. Bg5 {White prevents Nxe4.} Be7 9. Nxf6+ {This is White's best try in the 8.Bg5 line.} Nxf6 {Very often, our idea will be Bxf3-Qxf3-Qd5.} (9... Bxf6 {also possible.} 10. Bf4 $1) 10. c3 {[%cal Gf3e5] Most common move, but it allows Black to execute his idea:} Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qd5 $1 {we force the queens exchange.} 12. Qxd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 {White's hope is to play a long endgame with two bishops, but this structure is very good to face this scenario in the endgame.} (13. Bxe7 $6 Kxe7 $132 {We can play for more than equality in the endgame knight vs bishop.}) 13... a5 $5 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6] This is not a position where the two bishops are an advantage.}) (8. Qe2 {White's second most common move. transposes in Chapter 2.} Nxe4 9. Bxe4 Bxe4 10. Qxe4 c6 {This position is very safe and practical for Black. Although the engine always shows +0,20, this means nothing and practice has shown that Black is perfectly fine in this structure with only one knight and the dark squares bishop left.} 11. c4 Be7 12. Bf4 {very popular way to play the position.} O-O {[%cal Yf8e8,Yd7f8,Yf8g6] against the bishop on f4, our plan might be Re8-Nf8-Ng6.} 13. Rad1 {common, but we get a tempo against a2.} Qa5 {[%csl Ra2]} 14. a3 Rfe8 $132 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gd7f8,Gf8g6]}) (8. Re1 $5 {rare but serious.} Bxe4 9. Bxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 {[%csl Ge4] compared with the 8.Qe2 variation, White's rook might go on g4 or on h4 to create some attacking possibilities.} Be7 (10... c6 {was needed in the 8.Qe2 variation, but here it is not so urgent to play it. Very often we will play c7-c5 in one move.}) 11. Rg4 $1 {the most interesting option for White.} Bf6 {[%cal Ye6e5,Yc7c5] Safest option. We just need one tempo to play e5 or c5, and our position will be immediately fine.} 12. h4 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5] White prepares Bg5. This move was played only twice, but by two very strong players: Ivic and Saric. They scored 2/2.} c5 $1 $146 {Important novelty. We immediately create a counterplay in the center, not allowing White to have all the time to organize something serious on the kingside.} 13. Bg5 {The strongest move, according to the engine.} cxd4 14. Bxf6 {critical.} Qxf6 15. Rxd4 Nb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] if we play Nc6, our position will be great.}) (8. Ned2 {[%cal Yd2c4,Yc4e5] Flexible move. Sometimes, White might think about Nc4-Ne5.} Be7 {standard development.} 9. Re1 {[%cal Rc6e4,Gd2c4]} (9. b3 {too slow:} O-O 10. Bb2 b6 $1 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Yc6b7] We are in time to create a good b7 square for our bishop, and the position is equal.}) (9. Nc4 Be4 $11) 9... O-O 10. Nc4 Bd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] standard move.} 11. Nce5 (11. Ne3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 c5 $1 $11) 11... c5 $1 {important move, but easy.} 12. c4 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Qb6 $132 {at least fine for Black.}) (8. Nc3 $5 {Only 70 games, but it's the engine's recommendation and also a lot of authors have suggested it for White.} Be7 $1 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Yd7e5,Yf3e5] Black's best development. Be7 is better than Bd6 because after Re1-Ne5 we will be able to play Nxe5.} 9. Re1 a6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] very good move and it has been played only once. We want to play b5, taking space on the queenside and preparing Bb7-c5.} (9... O-O $6 {is dangerous because White can play} 10. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 $2 11. dxe5 Nd5 12. Qg4 $1 Nxc3 13. Bh6 $18) 10. Ne5 {this move was very strong against 9...00, but here we are fine after} (10. a4 $1 $146 {[%cal Rb7b5] The critical move. White prevents b5.} Bb4 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Yc3] we use the vulnerability of the b4 square and create pressure against Nc3.} 11. Bd2 {the most logical move.} O-O {only now we will play castle.} 12. Ne5 {White's best and only interesting continuation to play for the advantage. If not Ne5, we can continue playing useful moves, or even consider the Bxf3-Qxf3-c5 idea.} Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bxc3 $1 {important move.} 14. Bxc3 {and now, we have two possible directions.} Nd5 {I prefer this move.} 15. Bd2 {logical for White to keep the bishops, and now it's very important to play the following move:} f5 $1 {without this, we are much worse.} 16. exf6 {other moves are not interesting for White because our position will be very good and we will have easy play.} Qxf6 17. Qe2 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd5f4] White has two bishops and a better structure, but our pieces are very active and this allows us to equalize. Our key idea will be e5-Nf4.} Rae8 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gf6b2] b2 is now hanging.} 18. b3 {logical move and the best according to the engine.} e5 {[%cal Ye5e4,Yd5f4] we are ready for e4 or Nf4.}) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd5 $11 12. Qg4 $6 {was strong in the 9...00 variation, but here it's dubious:} Nxc3 13. Qxg7 $146 {critical.} (13. bxc3 Qd7 $1 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8] 000 next, and our position is better. The bishop on c6 became a very powerful piece.}) 13... Kd7 $3 {[%cal Gh8g8] fantastic idea shown by the engine. White doesn't have time for bxc3 because of Rg8.}) 8... Be7 $1 {the best development.} 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gf3e5] This move, in my opinion, is underrated. It might actually be the most challenging line against the Fort Knox Variation. With accurate play, however, Black can handle it.} (9. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] very popular development.} O-O 10. Bb2 b5 $5 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gc6a8,Gc7c5] positional option, my favorite one.}) (9. c4 {Very popular move and here we have an important idea:} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 c5 $1 {strong idea. We don't allow White to play with a risk-free small advantage as happens after 10...c6. We have transposed in Chapter 8 in the variation 9.c4 Bxf3 10.Qxf3 c5. Here, we have it at move 11 because White wasted a tempo for Qe2, and we wasted a tempo for c6.} 11. Be3 {most common move, but Black has many good ways here:} (11. Qxb7 $6 cxd4 $36 {[%cal Ye8g8,Yd7c5] 00-Nc5 next. White must already think about equality.}) 11... cxd4 {the easiest to make a draw.} 12. Bxd4 Nc5 $11) (9. Re1 {a standard move and also it's White's most common continuation.} O-O 10. c3 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yc3d4] In my opinion, this is White's best continuation. Not only it's a typical useful move, but it also prevents our Bxf3-Qxf3-c5 idea.} (10. Ne5 $2 {it's always important to check this move, but here it's not good:} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qd5 $1 {[%cal Rf2f4] key resource; without it, our position would be much worse.} 12. f3 $2 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Ng4 $1 $17 {[%cal Gg4f2] White is in serious troubles.}) 10... a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5a4] I like this move. We want to take space on the queenside.} 11. a4 {looks logical, because White stops a5-a4, but now we can use the following idea:} (11. Qe2 {White has to complete the development.} a4 $146 {[%csl Ga4] It's a novelty, but it's also a very logical continuation of our previous move.}) 11... Bd5 $5 {[%cal Gc7c5] we are ready for c5. The key point is that after}) 9... Bxf3 $1 {This is the right moment to capture on f3. Yes, it's a small concession, but White had to spend a tempo (Qe2) to provoke it.} (9... O-O $6 {in the last chaper, we have seen that after 9.Re1, 9...00 works very well, but here the situation is different for concrete reasons:} 10. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qd5 12. f4 $16 {[%csl Gf4]}) 10. Qxf3 c6 {This is the only case in the entire database where we willingly play this structure with c6 in a middlegame, without the pair of bishops and with White still holding a knight. The key advantages in our favor are White's poorly placed knight on g3 and the tempo lost with Qe2 followed by Qxf3.} (10... c5 $6 {our standard idea doesn't work here:} 11. dxc5 $1 {and concretely we cannot equalize, for example:} Nxc5 (11... O-O 12. Ne4 $16) 12. Bb5+ $1 $16 {A key move that gives White the advantage. The Bxf3-Qxf3-c5 idea is rarely effective when we haven’t castled yet.}) 11. Re1 {This is the approach I find most concerning: White slowly improves his position with Re1 and c3, creating no clear targets. Unlike c4, which makes ...c5 more effective, or b3, which invites ...Qa5 and ...Ba3, Re1-c3 leaves Black uncertain about the best plan.} (11. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White's most common continuation, but I am not scared about it because we have now a clear idea:} Qa5 {[%cal Ge7a3] I like this move because we positionally prevent Bb2.} 12. a3 $1 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Re7a3] White prevents Ba3.} (12. Bb2 $6 {allows} Ba3 $1 {our position is already more than fine.}) 12... Qd5 {I like this move. We offer the queens exchange, and if White wants to avoid it, he should go to e3 or f4 to defend the d4 pawn.} (12... h5 $5 $146 {deserves attention.} 13. Bb2 {natural move, but after it we have a good game.} h4 14. Ne2 g5 $5)) 11... O-O 12. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Ge1][%cal Yc1d2,Ya1d1] White is ready to continue with Bd2-Rad1, slowly improving his position.} a5 $5 {[%csl Ya5][%cal Ga5a4] This is my recommendation: when lacking a clear plan, the a5-a4 expansion is often an excellent solution.} 13. a4 {now that White has played a4, we are more ready for} (13. Bc2 $1 {[%csl Yc2] This is probably White's best move—it improves the position without creating any targets.} a4 {[%cal Gd8a5,Gf8e8] we play another useful move, and maybe we will consider Qa5 on the next one.} 14. a3 {the best, according to the engine, and now we can play} Qb6 $146 {[%csl Rc1] We stop the Bc1 development. Now, White has two options: the positional 15.Rb1, or the tactical 15.Nf5.}) 13... c5 $5 14. Qxb7 cxd4 15. cxd4 Nd5 $44 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Gd5b4,Ga8b8] we have the b4 square for our pieces, and this increases a lot our compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} *

