{[%evp 0,26,32,18,30,32,32,1,45,45,44,44,47,6,6,-55,-50,-87,-87,-141,-141,-132,-74,-64,-68,-88,-64,-47,-94]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 {This is the starting position of the Fort Knox variation. Our idea is to play Bc6-Nd7-Ngf6 and just complete the development. As we will see, our position is very solid, and we can play it relaying on the understanding. White needs to have prepared some idea against it to have a chance to fight for a small advantage.} 5. Nf3 {White's best and most natural continuation.} ({White also starts with} 5. Bd3 Bc6 6. Nf3 {that leads to the same position of the mainline.} (6. c3 {allows} Nf6 $1 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $11 {[%cal Gg1f3,Yc6f3,Yf6f3] When White plays Nf3, we can take Bxf3.})) (5. c4 {not a dangerous move, but we should know the right reaction.} Nf6 $1 {We force White's Ne4 to make a decision.} (5... Bc6 $6 {is our standard move, but in this concrete situation it is not good because after} 6. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Gd4] White has a positional advantage.}) 6. Nc3 {now we don't play Bc6, but} (6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. Nf3 Bb4+ $1 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 O-O 10. Be2 Rd8 11. O-O Bc6 $11) 6... c5 $1 7. d5 {looks critical, but it's harmless:} (7. Nf3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 $132 {we have a very comfortable and already preferable position, according to the engine.}) 7... Bd6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 exd5 10. cxd5 Bg4 $132 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf8e8,Ya7a6] no problem and we have very easy play.}) 5... Bc6 6. Neg5 $5 {[%cal Gf3e5] This is the only sideline at move six that we need to know. White's main idea is Ne5, which we must prevent. It’s a tricky line, so being familiar with it is crucial. With proper preparation, we’ll have every opportunity to play for the full point.} (6. Bd3 {is White's main move, and we will analyze it from the next chapter.}) 6... Nd7 $1 {[%cal Rf3e5] we stop Ne5.} (6... h6 $4 {is a huge mistake because of} 7. Nxf7 Kxf7 8. Ne5+ $18) 7. Nxf7 $5 {interesting sacrifice.} ({if White plays} 7. Bc4 {then} h6 {becomes strong.} 8. Nxf7 {only logical move for White.} Kxf7 9. d5 $1 {only move.} exd5 10. Bxd5+ Ke8 11. O-O Bd6 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7] It's a new position. Although White has some compensation, our position is objectively slightly better.}) (7. Bd3 {transposes in 6.Bd3.}) 7... Kxf7 8. Ng5+ Ke8 9. Bc4 $5 {White's most interesting continuation.} (9. Bd3 Qf6 $1 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yf6e6] we protect e6 and also defend from Qh5+.} 10. Qe2 $1 $146 {White's best continuation.} (10. O-O Be7 11. Re1 Nf8 $17) 10... Nb6 {[%cal Ge8d7,Ga8e8] not our only move, but probably it's the strongest. Our idea is to play Kd7-Re8.} 11. O-O (11. Nxh7 $6 Rxh7 12. Bxh7 Kf7 $15) 11... Kd7 $13 {uncelar position, but we are for sure not worse.}) (9. Nxe6 {objectively fine, but Black will have the chance to force a draw.} Qe7 10. Qe2 (10. Bc4 $4 {is a serious blunder.} Qb4+ $19) 10... Kf7 (10... Rc8 $5 {you can try to play this move if you don't want the draw.} 11. d5 $5 $146 (11. h4 $5 {engine's move. Minimum, we can still repeat the moves with Kf7-Ng5-Ke7-Ne6.}) (11. Bf4 $6 {all players have chosen this natural move, but here we are slightly better:} Ngf6 12. O-O-O Kf7 13. Re1 Kg8 $15) 11... Bxd5 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qxd5 Ngf6 {[%csl Re6] White regained the piece, but the position is still very concrete. There is a long forced line:} 14. Qb3 Nc5 15. Qb5+ Nfd7 16. Bc4 c6 17. Qa5 $1 Nxe6 18. O-O Qc5 19. Qxc5 Nexc5 20. Bg5 Nb6 $1 {According to the engine, White has enough compensation to get very close to a draw:} 21. Rfe1+ Kd7 22. Bf7 $1 Bd6 23. b4 Rhf8 24. bxc5 Bxc5 25. Be6+ Kc7 26. Bh4 Rce8 $11) 11. Ng5+ Ke8 12. Ne6 $1 {White has nothing better than to repeat the moves.} Kf7 $11) 9... Bxg2 $1 {very important move to remember.} 10. Rg1 $1 (10. Nxe6 $2 {in a recent game, GM Indijc lost the control and immediately lost with White:} Qe7 11. Qe2 Bxh1 12. Bg5 Ngf6 $19 {Indijc-Hakobyan, Aeroflot 2019.}) 10... Bd5 11. Nxe6 Bxe6 12. Bxe6 {we have more than one good move, but the strongest one is} Qe7 $1 13. Qe2 Kd8 $13 {[%cal Ya7a5,Ga8a6,Gg8f6,Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Ge7d6,Gh8e8] Unclear new position. Although White has some compensation to maintain the balance, we should be happy because we play for three results. We can continue the development with Ngf6-g6-Bg7-Qd6-Re8, sometimes a5-Ra6, and White should invent something otherwise he will just be without a piece.} *

