{[%evp 0,38,10,10,41,33,33,6,42,45,45,45,51,43,44,38,42,49,45,44,40,38,38,39,44,44,39,31,45,36,43,42,56,21,19,18,53,19,16,16,6]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Qe2 {White's second most common move.} Nxe4 9. Bxe4 Bxe4 10. Qxe4 c6 {This position is very safe and practical for Black. Although the engine always shows +0,20, this means nothing and practice has shown that Black is perfectly fine in this structure with only one knight and the dark squares bishop left.} 11. c4 (11. Bg5 Be7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11 {Black is immediately fine after the bishops exchange.} 13. Rad1 {let's my game Petrov-Jobava, 2016.} O-O (13... Qb4 $5 {was also an option.}) 14. a3 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Ya3b4,Re7b4] White prevents Qb4.} Rfd8 (14... Nf6 $5 $11 {[%cal Yb7b5,Rc2c4,Yb5c4] is an interesting way to play. We force the queen to leave the e4 square, and then we might play b7-b5, preventing c2-c4.}) 15. c4 {White managed to play c4, but the position is still equal, because we are very solid.} a5 {[%csl Ga5] a5 is almost always useful in this structure.} 16. Rfe1 Nf6 17. Qe5 Kf8 {waiting move, but maybe other more useful waiting moves were also possible.} 18. h3 a4 {ambitious move because I am fixing the structure.} (18... h6 {h6 was useful.}) 19. Rd2 (19. c5 $5 {was a possible idea for White.} Nd5 20. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] Nc4 next. Still equal, but at least White has a plan.} Qc7 {normal option.} (20... b5 {radical choice, but also good.} 21. cxb6 Nxb6 $11) 21. Nc4 (21. Qxc7 Nxc7 22. Nc4 Nb5 $11) 21... Qxe5 22. dxe5 b5 $1 23. cxb6 Rdb8 $11 {[%cal Gd5b6]}) 19... h6 20. Red1 Qd6 21. Kf1 $6 {in the endgame, I had a chances to overtake the initiative.} Qxe5 22. Nxe5 Ke7 (22... Ne4 $1 {was strong.} 23. Rd3 (23. Re2 $6 {allows} Nc5 $1 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5b3] Nb3 next, and White's position is also objectively difficult.}) 23... f6 24. Nf3 Nd6 25. Rc1 Kf7 $15 {/= also the engine gives a small plus to Black.}) 23. Rd3 Nd7 $11 {and the game soon ended in a draw.}) (11. b3 {[%csl Yf4][%cal Gc1b2,Yd7f8,Yf8g6,Yg6f4] popular approach. White wants to develop the bishop on b2. The bishop on b2 looks fantastic, but from my own experience I noticed that very often Black gets Nf8-Ng6 ideas in the middlegame, and White's f4 square might be vulnerable.} Be7 {Bd6 is also a good move.} 12. Bb2 O-O 13. c4 Qa5 {[%cal Ye7a3] not the only good move, but a typical idea. Sometimes Ba3 will be an option.} 14. Qc2 {let's follow a bit the game Ruiz-Burmakin, 2014.} Rfd8 15. Rad1 Ba3 (15... Bf6 $5 {[%cal Yb7b5] was another good option. Then we might play with b7-b5.}) 16. Ba1 Qh5 17. Rd3 Be7 $1 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Ge7f6] Black correctly undestands that the bishop belongs to f6.} 18. Rfd1 Qf5 19. h3 Nf8 {[%csl Yf4][%cal Gf8g6,Yg6f4] Nf8-Ng6 is a typical idea, especially when White's bishop is on b2 (or a1), because the f4 square might be vulnerable.} 20. Kh2 Ng6 21. g3 h5 $5 $36 {[%cal Gh5h4] Black starts a kingside play. Rd7, followed by Rad8, was also fine. It's clear that Black already has the initiative, and GM Burmakin later won the game.}) (11. Re1 {Useful move. White doesn't reveal his plans yet.} Be7 (11... Nf6 {also possible, if you want to avoid the Be7 Qg4 line, but White can get some small extra ideas against our knight on f6, that's why I prefer to delay this move for a bit. Still, objectively, our position is very fine.} 12. Qe2 Bd6 13. Bg5 $5 {extra option, but not so dangerous.} h6 14. Bh4 O-O 15. Rad1 Be7 $5 $11 {[%cal Gf6h5] Nh5 next.}) 12. Qg4 $5 {only interesting move for White.} O-O 13. Bh6 $1 (13. h4 $6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gd7f6] not good now because we still have the f6 square for our knight.}) 13... Bf6 14. h4 {White plays for the kingside initiative. Of course, our position is very solid and a lot of moves are possible.} (14. Rad1 {Normal move, but Black can equalize with the following idea:} Qa5 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ga5a2]} 15. a3 Qf5 $11 {not the only idea, but this one leads to an equal endgame.} (15... Rfe8 $5 {also fine. We wait h2-h4, and only then we will play Qf5.})) 14... c5 (14... Qb6 $5 15. b3 c5 $11 {[%cal Yb6c5] we can recapture on c5 with the queen.}) 15. dxc5 Nxc5 $11 {looks very fine for Black.}) (11. c3 {also useful move, but Re1 was more useful probably.} a5 $5 $132 {of course, other moves were also possible, but I like to reply with a useful move as well.}) (11. Bf4 Be7 (11... Nf6 $5 12. Qe2 Bd6 $11 {good extra option.}) 12. c4 {transposes in 11.c4.}) 11... Be7 12. Bd2 $5 (12. Qg4 {this idea is not fantastic connected with the c2-c4 move. If White wanted to play with Qg4, it was better for White to start with 11.Re1 as we have seen.} O-O 13. Bh6 Bf6 {[%csl Rc4]} 14. Rad1 Qa5 $132 {[%cal Ga5f5] When it will be needed, we will consider the move Qf5.}) (12. Bf4 {very popular way to play the position.} O-O {[%cal Yf8e8,Yd7f8,Yf8g6] against the bishop on f4, our plan might be Re8-Nf8-Ng6.} 13. Rfe1 (13. Rad1 {common, but we get a tempo against a2.} Qa5 {[%csl Ra2]} 14. a3 Rfe8 $132 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gd7f8,Gf8g6]}) 13... Qa5 $132 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ga8c8,Yd7f8,Yf8g6] We can continue with Re8-Rc8-Nf8-Ng6. Equal and playbable position.}) 12... O-O 13. b4 $5 {White takes space on the queenside, and it was tried in the game Seirawan-Kortschnoj, 1993.} (13. Bc3 {is similar to 11.b3, we can play Re8-Nf8-Ng6. Our bishop will probably go on f6 later.} Re8 14. Rad1 Qc7 $132 {[%cal Ga8d8]}) 13... Re8 14. Rab1 (14. Qe2 Bf6 $1 15. Bc3 Qc7 $11 {[%cal Yc6c5,Ye6e5] we can consider e5 or c5 on the next move.}) (14. a4 Bf6 $1 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5] we will play for e5.}) 14... Bf6 {[%cal Ge6e5] we prepare e5.} 15. Rfe1 Rc8 {useful move.} (15... e5 $5 {also possible.} 16. d5 cxd5 17. Qxd5 b6 $132 {[%cal Ga8c8]}) 16. Bf4 {White prevents e5, looks logical.} b5 $5 {[%csl Yb4] This is a serious option, especially when White has played b2-b4.} (16... Nf8 $132 {[%cal Gf8g6] standard idea.}) 17. c5 a5 18. a3 axb4 19. axb4 Be7 $11 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gf6d5] Nf6-Nd5 next.} *

