{[%evp 0,38,25,16,41,31,37,45,33,36,52,40,45,45,55,50,55,51,42,47,38,38,42,38,47,44,44,37,37,41,58,57,52,31,38,21,25,14,28,23,16]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Re1 $5 {rare but serious.} Bxe4 9. Bxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 {[%csl Ge4] compared with the 8.Qe2 variation, White's rook might go on g4 or on h4 to create some attacking possibilities.} Be7 (10... c6 {was needed in the 8.Qe2 variation, but here it is not so urgent to play it. Very often we will play c7-c5 in one move.}) 11. Rg4 $1 {the most interesting option for White.} (11. c4 O-O {[%cal Gc7c5] we want to play c7-c5.} 12. b3 (12. Qe2 Re8 $11 {[%csl Ye7][%cal Ge8e7,Gc7c5] First, we protect the bishop on e7, and then we will play c7-c5.} (12... c5 $6 13. d5 {is White's idea.} Nf6 14. Re3 Ng4 15. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 16. Qxe6+ Kh8 17. Qxg4 $36)) 12... c5 13. Bb2 Bf6 $11) (11. Bf4 {most common move, but then why did White take with the rook on e4?} Nf6 12. Re1 c5 $11 {very comfortable for Black.}) 11... Bf6 {[%cal Ye6e5,Yc7c5] Safest option. We just need one tempo to play e5 or c5, and our position will be immediately fine.} (11... O-O {risky, but also holds.} 12. Bh6 Bf6 13. Ng5 $1 $146 Re8 $1 {[%cal Yd7f8] only move. We prepare Nf8.} 14. h4 $5 (14. Qd3 Nf8 $11) 14... Qe7 $1 {[%csl Yf7][%cal Gg8h8,Ye7f7] We protect f7, and Kh8 is our next idea.} 15. Ne4 g6 16. Nxf6+ (16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. hxg5 h6 $1 18. gxh6 Nf6 $132 {For the computer this is fine.}) 16... Nxf6 17. Bg5 h6 $1 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. h5 e5 $1 20. hxg6 fxg6 21. d5 e4 $11 {the engine thinks that it's equal, but it could be slightly unpleasant over the board.}) 12. h4 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5] White prepares Bg5. This move was played only twice, but by two very strong players: Ivic and Saric. They scored 2/2.} (12. Bg5 Bxg5 {the easiest.} (12... h6 13. Bxf6 (13. Be3 $5 {[%csl Rh6] h6 might be problematic in the future, but we can play}) 13... Qxf6 14. Qe2 O-O $11 {Sukovic-Rakhmanov, 2023.}) 13. Rxg5 (13. Nxg5 h5 14. Rg3 h4 15. Rg4 Nf6 16. Rf4 Qe7 $36 {[%cal Ge8c8] 000 next, and Black already has a small initiative.}) 13... O-O $11 {[%cal Gd8f6] Qf6 next, and Black is very safe.}) 12... c5 $1 $146 {Important novelty. We immediately create a counterplay in the center, not allowing White to have all the time to organize something serious on the kingside.} (12... Qe7 {Saric-Neef, 2022.} 13. Qe2 $1 $146 O-O 14. h5 $36 {looks dangerous.}) (12... c6 {solid, but allows White to develop an initiative.} 13. Qe2 Qa5 14. c4 O-O 15. Bd2 Qf5 16. Re4 {[%cal Gg2g4] g4 is White's idea.} h5 $14 {necessary move, but White has a lot of interesting options now. Ivic-Markus, 2022.}) 13. Bg5 {The strongest move, according to the engine.} (13. c3 {harmless.} cxd4 14. cxd4 Nb6 $11 {[%cal Gb6d5,Ge8g8,Ya8c8]}) (13. h5 $5 cxd4 14. h6 Rg8 $1 $13 {[%cal Gg7g5] we prepare g5. This looks very unclear, but it's 0.00 and we play for three results.}) 13... cxd4 14. Bxf6 {critical.} (14. Rxd4 Qc7 $11) (14. Qe2 $5 {to get a game.} O-O 15. Rxd4 Qc7 16. Bf4 e5 (16... Qc6 $5 17. Rd6 Qa4 18. c4 Nc5 $132 {also possible.}) 17. Bg3 Rfe8 $132 {White can play, but it's not risk-free and we have also our ideas. The engine evaluates +0,15.}) 14... Qxf6 15. Rxd4 Nb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] if we play Nc6, our position will be great.} 16. Ne5 $1 O-O {[%csl Ye5] White must defend the knight.} 17. Qh5 Rc8 $1 {preparing Nc6.} 18. Rad1 Nc6 19. Nxc6 Rxc6 $11 {Equal.} *

