{[%evp 0,28,18,25,31,18,26,-8,47,47,47,45,54,50,53,53,50,44,36,34,50,41,67,32,38,48,46,46,44,54,43]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Bg5 {White prevents Nxe4.} Be7 (8... h6 {also possible, but could be dangerous in the future:} 9. Nxf6+ Nxf6 10. Bf4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gf3e5] White wants to play Ne5, and one day we might regret that our pawn is on h6, because White could have Bxh6 ideas.}) 9. Nxf6+ {This is White's best try in the 8.Bg5 line.} (9. Qe2 Bxe4 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe7 Nc3 $5 {not forced, but looks nice. We want to force White's queen to go on c3, where it could be misplaced.} (11... Qxe7 {also possible, of course.} 12. Qxe4 c6 $11 {We have already seen this position in the 8.Qe2 chapter.}) 12. Qc4 (12. bxc3 Qxe7 $132 {Very good for Black.}) 12... Qxe7 13. Qxc3 Nf6 $11 {[%csl Rc3]}) (9. Ned2 O-O {worse version for White of the 8.Ned2 variation, because the inclusion of Bg5 and 00 is good for Black.} 10. Nc4 (10. Re1 b6 $132) 10... Bb5 $5 11. a4 Ba6 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5] c5 next.}) (9. Ng3 O-O {worse version for White of the 8.Ng3 variation, because the inclusion of Bg5 and 00 is good for Black.} 10. c3 (10. Re1 Bxf3 $5 11. Qxf3 c5 $1 {Strong idea.} 12. dxc5 (12. Qxb7 cxd4 $132 {[%cal Gd7c5]}) 12... Nxc5 13. Bc4 Qb6 $11) (10. c4 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 c5 $1 $11) 10... Bd5 $5 {[%cal Gc7c5] we prepare c5.} 11. Ne5 (11. c4 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 c5 $11) (11. b4 {[%cal Rc7c5] White prevents b4, but we can play} b6 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5,Yd5b7] c5 next, and we also have the b7 square for our bishop.}) 11... c5 (11... Nxe5 $5 {more fighting option.} 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Bxe7 (13. Bf4 Bg5 $132) 13... Qxe7 14. Re1 Qh4 15. Be4 Rad8 $1 16. Bxd5 Nb6 17. c4 c6 $11) 12. c4 Bc6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Bc2 Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 a5 $11 {[%csl Rg3] Our pieces are very good, while the knight on g3 is bad.}) (9. Re1 $2 {doesn't work for tactical reasons.} Nxe4 10. Bxe7 Nxf2 $1 $15 {important intermezzo.}) (9. Bxf6 Nxf6 {White should be already careful, because we have two bishops.} 10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Re1 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gf3e5]} Bxf3 $5 (11... O-O 12. Ne5 $11 {[%cal Rd8d4,Yd3h7] We cannot take on d4 because of Bxh7+.}) 12. Qxf3 c6 13. c3 O-O $132 {[%csl Yd3,Gf6] Typical situation for this line. According to the engine, it's equal, but in a practical game Black has better chances in the opposite color bishops positions. The score here is 37,5%.}) 9... Nxf6 {Very often, our idea will be Bxf3-Qxf3-Qd5.} (9... Bxf6 {also possible.} 10. Bf4 $1 (10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Be2 O-O $11 {is immediately fine for Black.}) 10... O-O 11. Re1 Bxf3 {sooner or later, we will have to play it.} 12. Qxf3 c6 $14 {/= typical position of this line, if things go slightly worse. We are very solid, and we can play it, but objectively White has a small edge. Remember, in the endgame (without queens), we are not afraid of the two bishops, but in the middlegame, things might be slightly unpleasant if we don't have anything concrete.}) 10. Bf4 $1 $146 {White's strongest move, but it's a novelty.} (10. Ne5 $6 Qxd4 11. Nxc6 bxc6 $15 {White doesn't ahve enough compensation for the pawn.}) (10. c3 {Most common move, but it allows Black to execute his idea:} Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qd5 $1 {we force the queens exchange.} 12. Qxd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 {White's hope is to play a long endgame with two bishops, but this structure is very good to face this scenario in the endgame.} (13. Bxe7 $6 Kxe7 $132 {We can play for more than equality in the endgame knight vs bishop.}) 13... a5 $5 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6] This is not a position where the two bishops are an advantage.}) (10. Re1 $5 {important line.} Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qd5 $1 12. Qg3 $5 $146 (12. Qxd5 Nxd5 $11 {immediately fine for Black.}) 12... Nh5 {Concrete and principled move, but here you need to remember.} (12... O-O-O {also possible, White will play} 13. Bd2 h5 $5 $13 {White has two bishops, but we also have ideas.}) 13. Qxc7 Qxg5 14. Re5 $1 Qh4 15. g3 Qxd4 (15... Qh3 $4 16. Bf5 $18) 16. Qxb7 $1 (16. Rxh5 Qxb2 $11 {[%cal Gb2b6] Qb6 next, and it's equal.}) 16... O-O 17. Rxh5 g6 18. Qxe7 (18. Rb5 Rab8 $1 19. Qxe7 Rxb5 20. Bxb5 Qxb2 $11 {[%csl Ra1,Rb5][%cal Gb2b5,Gb2a1]}) 18... Qxb2 $1 19. Re1 gxh5 20. Qg5+ Qg7 21. Qxh5 Rad8 $13 {[%cal Gd8d5] Rd5 next. White has compensation, but no more.}) 10... O-O (10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qd5 $2 {[%csl Rc7] is no longer possible because the c7 pawn is now hanging.} 12. Bxc7 $16) 11. c3 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gc3d4] White protects d4.} (11. Re1 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Qxd4 13. Bxc7 Qd5 $11) 11... Be4 $1 {strong move.} 12. Bxe4 (12. Be2 $6 c5 $36 {Black is already preferable.}) 12... Nxe4 13. Qb3 Rb8 14. Rfe1 Nf6 $132 {Typical solid position, where the engine shows +0,15, but we are very solid and we can play a long game. White doesn't have any concrete ideas, and that's very important.} *

