{[%evp 0,20,24,16,37,32,28,-5,43,47,48,48,48,56,48,43,43,43,43,31,30,23,31]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Ned2 {[%cal Yd2c4,Yc4e5] Flexible move. Sometimes, White might think about Nc4-Ne5.} Be7 {standard development.} ({I have also tried} 8... g6 {which is also possible against 8.Ned2.} 9. b3 Bg7 10. Ba3 Bf8 11. Bb2 Bg7 {White can repeat the moves, or play on.} 12. Qe2 $14 {playable, but objectively slightly better for White.}) 9. Qe2 {6th most common move, but it's the most challenging line, in my opinion.} (9. b3 {too slow:} O-O 10. Bb2 b6 $1 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Yc6b7] We are in time to create a good b7 square for our bishop, and the position is equal.} 11. c4 (11. Qe2 Bb7 12. Ba6 Qc8 $11 {Timofeev-Pridorozhni.}) 11... Bb7 {[%cal Gc7c5] We play for c5.} 12. Qe2 c5 13. Rad1 Qc7 $11 {Absolutely fine position. For example:} 14. Ne4 (14. Rfe1 Rfe8 $5 $132 {This move is always useful.}) 14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 a6 $11 {[%cal Rd4b5,Gf8d8] Against Nb5. Our next move could be Rfd8.}) (9. Nc4 Bd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] the move that I like the most. Our idea is to play c5.} (9... O-O 10. Na5 $1 $14 {might be a bit unpleasant, for example:} Bxf3 11. Qxf3 c6 12. Nxb7 Qc7 13. Nc5 Nxc5 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bd2 $14 {Here the two bishops give White some long-term hope.}) (9... a5 $5 {possible move against Na5.} 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Nce5 Bd5 $5 {[%cal Gc7c5] we provoke c4.} 12. c4 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 c5 $1 $11) (9... Be4 {safe move.} 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11. Bf4 $5 $146 {the bext, according to the engine.} (11. d5 {most common continuation, but Black can equalize:} exd5 12. Qxd5 Ndc5 $11) 11... Nef6 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Rad1 Nd5 14. Bg3 b5 15. Na5 Qb8 16. Nc6 Qb7 17. Nxe7+ Nxe7 $11) 10. Ne3 {critical.} (10. Nce5 c5 $1 11. dxc5 (11. Nxf7 $2 {was tried in the game Stellwagen-Werle. Black got scared and took on f3, which is a bad move.} Kxf7 $1 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. c4 h6 $1 14. cxd5 hxg5 15. dxe6 Nf8 $17 (15... Nb8 $5 $17 {[%cal Gb8c6]})) (11. c4 Bxf3 12. Nxf3 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Qb6 $132 {very comfortable for Black.}) 11... Bxc5 12. Bf4 (12. Bg5 Qc7 $11) 12... O-O $132 {playable and no problems for Black.}) 10... Be4 11. Bxe4 (11. Re1 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O $132 {[%cal Gc7c5] no problem.}) (11. Be2 $6 c5 $1 $15 {already slightly better for Black.}) 11... Nxe4 12. d5 {critical move.} (12. c4 O-O 13. Qc2 {Pichot-Rustemov.} Ng5 $1 {it's very good for us to exchange the knights.} (13... Nef6 $6 14. b4 $1 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2] White can play on the queenside.}) 14. Nd2 (14. Nxg5 Bxg5 15. b4 (15. Bd2 c5 $11) 15... Qf6 $5 (15... a5 16. b5 c5 $11) 16. Bb2 Qg6 $11) 14... f5 $5 {[%cal Yf5f4,Yc7c5] f4 or c5 could be our idea.} 15. f4 Nf7 16. Nf3 Nf6 $11 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gf6e4,Yc7c5] c5 next, and it's equal.}) (12. Qd3 Nef6 13. c4 O-O 14. b3 c6 15. Bb2 a5 $132 {just playable.}) 12... exd5 13. Qxd5 (13. Nxd5 O-O 14. Re1 Ndf6 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 $11) 13... Nd6 $1 {no games, but this might be an important position.} (13... Ndc5 $6 14. Re1 $1 $16) 14. Ng4 {[%cal Gc1f4] White wants to develop the bishop on f4.} (14. b3 O-O 15. Bb2 c6 16. Qh5 Bf6 $11) 14... O-O (14... h5 $5 {engine move.} 15. Nge5 c6 16. Qd3 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 O-O $11) 15. Bf4 Nb6 16. Qb3 Qc8 17. Ne3 Ne4 $5 $132 {[%cal Ge7c5] We prepare Bc5. It's a playable position.}) (9. c4 O-O 10. Re1 (10. b3 b6 11. Bb2 Bb7 {transposes in 9.b3.}) 10... b6 $132 {[%cal Gc6b7,Gc7c5] typical idea. We want to play Bb7 and c5.}) (9. c3 {normal move, but after} O-O {White's normal moves are Re1 or Qe2, and they transpose in 9.Re1 or 9.Qe2.}) (9. Re1 O-O 10. Nc4 (10. b3 $6 {Giri-Nihal. Very unfortunate move for White.} Bb4 $1 $15 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Gb4c3]}) (10. c3 {two ways for Black:} b6 {[%cal Gc6b7,Gc7c5] Bb7-c5. We have time to play this idea now.} (10... Bd5 $5 {[%cal Gc7c5] With c7-c5 idea.}) 11. Nc4 Bb7 $132 {against 10.Nc4, b6 is not so good, that's why 10.Nc4 is considered more accurate than 10.c3.}) 10... Bd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] standard move.} (10... b6 {not so good now because of} 11. Nce5 Bb7 12. Qe2 $1 c5 $2 13. Ng5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rf7] concrete problems.}) (10... Bb5 $5 {deserves attention.} 11. a4 Ba6 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5] c5 next, and Black is fine.}) 11. Nce5 (11. Ne3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 c5 $1 $11) 11... c5 $1 {important move, but easy.} 12. c4 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Qb6 $132 {at least fine for Black.}) 9... O-O 10. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Yd1][%cal Gf3e5,Yd1d8] Best move. White prepares Ne5, which is a very serious idea.} (10. c3 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc6b7,Gc7c5] Bb7-c5 next, no problem for Black.}) (10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd5 $5 {my recommendation.} (11... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5] we want to play Nc5.} 12. Nb3 $1 (12. Rd1 Nc5 $11) 12... Nc5 13. Nxc5 Bxc5 14. Qg4 $1 {if we are not precise, it might be slightly unpleasant} f5 $1 15. exf6 Qxf6 {Probably equal.} 16. Kh1 $1 {you need to be accurate, but there are many good ways, for example:} (16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. Qxc5 Bxg2 $1 {key idea.} 19. Kxg2 Qf3+ 20. Kg1 Qg4+ $11 {perpetual.}) 16... Bxf2 17. Be3 Qh4 18. Qxe6+ Kh8 19. Rxf2 Rxf2 20. Bxf2 Qxf2 21. Qh3 h6 22. Rf1 Qc5 $11 {[%cal Ga8f8] Rf8 next.}) 12. Qg4 Nb4 13. Be4 Kh8 $1 {useful move against future Bh6 ideas.} 14. a3 Bxe4 15. Qxe4 Nc6 16. Nf3 Qd5 $11 {Equal and playable.}) 10... Nd5 {[%cal Yd5f4,Yd5b4] my recommendation. We have Nf4 or Nb4 ideas.} (10... b6 {looks normal, but after} 11. Ne5 Bb7 12. Ndf3 Qc8 13. c4 $14 {Black can experience some problems.}) (10... Bxf3 {engine line, but in a game it's easier to play for White:} 11. Nxf3 c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bf4 $14) 11. g3 $1 $146 {Only move that can pose some problems, but it's a novelty.} (11. Nc4 Nb4 $1 12. Be4 Bxe4 13. Qxe4 {many moves are fine like Nd5, b5 or c5.} Nd5 $11) (11. Ne5 $2 Nf4 $19) (11. Ne4 Nb4 12. Bc4 {Kobalia-Solak.} b5 $1 $146 13. Bxb5 Bxb5 14. Qxb5 Nxc2 15. Rb1 Nb4 16. a3 Nd5 $11 {Just equal.}) 11... Nb4 {most interesting option.} (11... b6 {also possible.} 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nb4 14. Be4 Qe8 15. c3 Bxe4 16. Nxe4 Nc6 17. Bf4 Rd8 $132 {Maybe it's not 100% equal for the engine, but it looks very close to equality.}) 12. Be4 Nf6 $1 {very sound move, and White will need to find a very difficult idea if he wants to fight for something.} (12... Bxe4 13. Nxe4 $14 {small plus for White.}) 13. c4 $1 {very difficult move to play because White has played g3, and now needs to allow the exchange of his light squares bishop for a knight.} (13. Bxc6 {is just equal.} Nxc6 14. Nc4 Qd5 15. Nce5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qe4 $1 17. Kf1 Qxe2+ 18. Kxe2 Nd5 $11) 13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 {[%csl Rb4] We have some problems with the knight on b4.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gb4a6,Ya2a3,Rb2b4] securing the a6 square (no a3-b4 for White).} 15. a3 Na6 16. Bf4 b6 $14 {For the engine this is +0,20, but for a human looks normal, for example:} 17. d5 (17. Re1 Bb7 18. Rad1 Qd7 {[%csl Ye6][%cal Yf7f6] We defend e6, and want to play f6.} 19. Ne5 Qc8 20. Nc3 f6 21. Nd3 Rd8 $1 22. Qxe6+ Qxe6 23. Rxe6 Rxd4 $1 24. Rxe7 Rad8 25. Bxc7 Nxc7 26. Rxc7 Bf3 27. Re1 Rxd3 $44 {[%csl Gf3] full compensation.}) 17... exd5 18. cxd5 Bb7 19. d6 cxd6 20. Nxd6 Bxd6 21. Rxd6 Qc8 22. Rxb6 Nc5 $44 {[%csl Rf3,Rg2] Full compensation because the light squares might be a problem for White very soon.} 23. Rc1 Re8 $1 24. Ne5 Qh3 25. Qf1 Qxf1+ 26. Kxf1 Ba6+ 27. Kg2 Nd3 28. Nxd3 Bxd3 $11 {[%cal Ga5a4] drawish endgame. We will play a5-a4 probably.} *

