{[%evp 0,44,14,18,18,18,31,3,36,47,47,47,45,53,54,44,53,44,40,40,44,33,35,32,35,28,28,35,35,39,35,42,44,41,34,34,59,59,61,38,74,41,46,-7,25,22,22]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Nc3 $5 {Only 70 games, but it's the engine's recommendation and also a lot of authors have suggested it for White.} Be7 $1 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Yd7e5,Yf3e5] Black's best development. Be7 is better than Bd6 because after Re1-Ne5 we will be able to play Nxe5.} (8... g6 $5 {possible, but a bit risky:} 9. Ne5 $14) (8... Bd6 {is less good than Be7:} 9. Re1 Bxf3 ({if we play} 9... a6 {like in the mainline, then after} 10. Ne5 $1 $16 {[%cal Rd7e5] we cannot play Nxe5.}) 10. Qxf3 c6 11. Bd2 O-O 12. g4 $40 {typical position that we should avoid.}) 9. Re1 (9. Bf4 {is not dangerous, and now we have an interesting atypical option:} Nf8 $5 $146 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf8g6] Ng6 next, gaining a tempo against White's Bf4.} (9... O-O {also fine of course.}) 10. Bb5 {critical because if we play Bxb5, after Nxb5 there are some concrete issues.} Bd7 $1 $11 {[%cal Gf8g6] calm move. Ng6 next, and it's equal.}) (9. Qe2 {worse than Re1, because after} O-O 10. Ne5 {key idea of the 8.Nc3 variation.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 {[%cal Re2g4,Gd7e5] White doesn't have the key move Qg4 because of Nxe5.} 12. Rd1 Qe8 {[%cal Gd7c5,Ga8d8] we remove the queen from the 'd' file, and want to continue with Nc5-Rd8.} 13. Nb5 {looks critical.} (13. Bb5 Nb6 $11) 13... Bxb5 14. Bxb5 Rd8 $11 {[%cal Gc7c6,Yd7c5] c6-Nc5 next and it's equal. White is not in time to stabilize and use the two bishops.}) 9... a6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] very good move and it has been played only once. We want to play b5, taking space on the queenside and preparing Bb7-c5.} (9... O-O {is dangerous because White can play} 10. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 $2 {principled but bad.} (10... Nd5 {best engine move, but after it we are of course slightly worse in many ways.}) 11. dxe5 Nd5 (11... Nd7 12. Qg4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ye1e5]}) 12. Qg4 $1 $40 {White has a huge kingside attack.}) (9... Bxf3 {the usual opinion is that Black has to go for this concession, and after} 10. Qxf3 c6 11. h4 $5 $36 {White has the initiative. I agree with the evaluation, but I don't agree with the fact that we must play 9...Bxf3.}) 10. a4 $1 $146 {[%cal Rb7b5] The critical move. White prevents b5.} (10. Ne5 {this move was very strong against 9...00, but here we are fine after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd5 $11 12. Qg4 $6 {was strong in the 9...00 variation, but here it's dubious:} ({White's best continuation is to force the equality with} 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Be4 Qxd1 14. Bxc6+ Qd7 15. Bxd7+ Kxd7 $11) 12... Nxc3 13. Qxg7 $146 {critical.} (13. bxc3 Qd7 $1 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8] 000 next, and our position is better. The bishop on c6 became a very powerful piece.}) 13... Kd7 $3 {[%cal Gh8g8] fantastic idea shown by the engine. White doesn't have time for bxc3 because of Rg8.} 14. Bf1 {only move.} (14. bxc3 $2 Rg8 $19 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gg8g2]}) 14... Nd5 15. c4 {and now we can give back the piece:} Qg8 16. Qxg8 Raxg8 17. cxd5 Bxd5 $15 {We have a preferable endgame.}) ({if White plays a useful move like} 10. Bf4 {then after} b5 $11 {[%cal Gc6b7,Yc7c5] Bb7-c5 next, and our position is absolutely fine. Take note that Ne5 is no longer an issue, because we just play Bb7 as mentioned.}) 10... Bb4 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Yc3] we use the vulnerability of the b4 square and create pressure against Nc3.} (10... O-O $2 {is once again bad because of} 11. Ne5 $1 $16) 11. Bd2 {the most logical move.} O-O {only now we will play castle.} (11... a5 $5 {also deserves attention.}) 12. Ne5 {White's best and only interesting continuation to play for the advantage. If not Ne5, we can continue playing useful moves, or even consider the Bxf3-Qxf3-c5 idea.} (12. h3 b6 $132 {normal game.} (12... Bxf3 $5 13. Qxf3 c5 {is very often an interesting option.} 14. Qxb7 Qa5 $44)) 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bxc3 $1 {important move.} 14. Bxc3 {and now, we have two possible directions.} (14. bxc3 $6 Qd5 $15) 14... Nd5 {I prefer this move.} (14... Qd5 {is also fine, but you need to be ready for an endgame:} 15. Bf1 Qxd1 16. Rexd1 Nd5 17. Be1 Ne7 $14 {[%cal Ge7g6] Ng6 next. According to the engine, Black is fine, but over the board it could be slightly unpleasant against the two bishops.}) 15. Bd2 {logical for White to keep the bishops, and now it's very important to play the following move:} (15. Qg4 {Qg4 was an issue when White's bishop was on c1, but here it's nothing:} Nxc3 16. bxc3 h6 $11 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3][%cal Gd8g5] Qg5 next, with full equality.}) 15... f5 $1 {without this, we are much worse.} 16. exf6 {other moves are not interesting for White because our position will be very good and we will have easy play.} (16. Qh5 Qe7 $132 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ga8d8,Yd5b4] Rad8 or Nb4 somewhere. We have a lot of moves, and our position is for sure not worse with our very strong Bc6.}) 16... Qxf6 17. Qe2 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd5f4] White has two bishops and a better structure, but our pieces are very active and this allows us to equalize. Our key idea will be e5-Nf4.} Rae8 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gf6b2] b2 is now hanging.} 18. b3 {logical move and the best according to the engine.} e5 {[%cal Ye5e4,Yd5f4] we are ready for e4 or Nf4.} 19. Be4 {[%csl Ge4] White prevents Nf4 and the bishop on e4 looks good.} (19. Rad1 Nf4 20. Bxf4 exf4 $11) 19... Kh8 {[%cal Gd5f4] prophylactic move against Qc4+.} (19... Nf4 $2 20. Qc4+ $1 Kh8 21. Bxc6 Qxc6 22. Qxc6 bxc6 23. Re4 $18 {positional disaster.}) (19... Re6 $5 {I like this generally useful move which also prevents Qc4+.}) 20. Rad1 (20. f3 $5 {engine move.} Nf4 21. Qf2 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 Qg6 {[%cal Gf4h3] Nh3 is a big threat.} 23. Bxf4 (23. Kh1 $4 Nh3 $1 24. gxh3 Qxe4 $19) 23... exf4 24. Rae1 h6 $11 {Equal.}) 20... Nf4 21. Bxf4 (21. Qf3 $4 {tactical blunder.} Nh3+ $1 $19) (21. Qe3 Rd8 $11) 21... exf4 22. Qd3 h6 $11 {Full equality.} *

