{[%evp 0,46,30,11,36,22,22,-1,44,45,45,45,41,44,44,44,44,36,28,31,45,48,72,51,57,42,49,37,37,34,20,29,41,45,46,36,43,45,51,27,36,39,39,35,31,12,10,-53,-83]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Ng3 {White's mainline, by far. 8.Ng3 has been played in around 50% of games that have reached this position.} Be7 $1 {the best development.} (8... Bd6 $6 {our bishop is worse on d6, for the following reason:} 9. Re1 O-O 10. Ne5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) ({I have also tried} 8... g6 {but it's objectively risky.} 9. h4 $5 $146 {the most annoying idea, but other moves are also possible.} Bg7 10. c3 {not easy to play for Black:} O-O (10... h5 11. Ng5 $16) (10... h6 11. Bc2 O-O 12. h5 g5 13. Nxg5 $1 $16) 11. h5 $16 {So I don't recommend to play 8...g6.}) 9. c4 {Very popular move and here we have an important idea:} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 c5 $1 {strong idea. We don't allow White to play with a risk-free small advantage as happens after 10...c6.} (10... c6 11. Bf4 $14 {playable, but objectively White is slightly better.}) 11. d5 $1 {critical.} (11. Qxb7 $6 cxd4 $36 {[%cal Ye8g8,Yd7c5] 00-Nc5 next. White must already think about equality.}) (11. Be3 {most common move, but Black has many good ways here:} cxd4 {the easiest to make a draw.} (11... Qb6 $5 12. dxc5 (12. d5 Ne5 13. Qe2 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Rd8 $1 15. Qa3 O-O $11) 12... Bxc5 $11) (11... O-O {also possible.} 12. Rad1 (12. Qxb7 cxd4 13. Bxd4 Nc5 14. Bxc5 Bxc5 $132 {[%csl Gc5] Our bishop is very strong.}) 12... cxd4 13. Bxd4 Qc7 $132) 12. Bxd4 Nc5 13. Bxc5 Bxc5 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Qf6 $1 16. Bxb7 Qxf3 17. Bxf3 Rb8 18. b3 Ke7 $11 {[%csl Gc5] just draw. Our bishop is too strong, and White's extra pawn is useless.}) 11... Ne5 12. Qe2 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 O-O (13... exd5 {the engine thinks that it's also possible, but I am a bit afraid of} 14. Nf5 O-O {White has many moves here to put an unpleasant pressure.} 15. Qg3 $36 (15. Bg5 $36)) 14. Rd1 exd5 15. cxd5 Re8 $1 $146 16. Qf3 {strongest move according to the engine.} (16. d6 $2 Bxd6 $1 {important tactical deatail.} 17. Qxd6 Re1+ $19) (16. Bf4 Bd6 17. Qf3 Bxf4 18. Qxf4 Qb6 19. Rd2 Rad8 $11 {just equal.}) 16... Qb6 {The position is balanced. We should just be careful about d6 or Nf5 ideas.} (16... Qd7 $5 17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Rac1 Bxf4 19. Qxf4 Qb5 20. d6 b6 $132 {equal with concrete moves.}) 17. a4 $5 {engine's line.} (17. Nf5 Bf8 $11 {[%cal Yg7g6,Yf6e4] g6 or Ne4 next, and no problems.}) (17. b3 {normal move.} Rad8 18. Bb2 Nd7 $1 $11 {[%cal Ge7f6] Bf6 next, with equality.}) (17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Bg5 (18. Bxd6 $6 Qxd6 19. Nf5 Qe5 20. d6 Rad8 $15 {[%csl Rd6] good example which shows that the d6 pawn can also become a weakness.}) 18... Be5 $11) 17... Qb4 $5 {[%cal Yb4g4] sometimes we will have Qg4 ideas.} (17... Bd6 {I don't like this move, because after} 18. Nf5 $1 $14 {we should probably lose a tempo and go back on f8.}) 18. d6 $1 (18. h3 {against Qg4.} Rad8 19. Nf5 Qe4 $1 $11 {once we exchange the queens, our position is not worse for sure, and maybe slightly better.}) 18... Bf8 19. Bd2 $1 {We're still following the engine's recommendation.} (19. Bg5 Re6 $1 20. Nf5 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8e8] Rae8 next, with very good counterplay. 0.00 also according to the engine.}) 19... Qb6 20. Bc3 Bxd6 $5 {if it works, this might be an easy draw.} (20... Re6 {also possible, but maybe slightly more risky:} 21. Nf5 Ne4 22. a5 Qb5 $1 {only move.} 23. a6 Rd8 $1 $11 {only move. If you trust the engine, you can play also 20...Re6.}) 21. a5 {looks critical.} (21. Nf5 Be5 22. Bxe5 Rxe5 23. Nxg7 Kxg7 24. Qg3+ Ng4 $1 25. Qxg4+ Qg6 $11 {very similar to 11.a5.}) (21. Bxf6 Bxg3 22. Bxg7 Bxh2+ 23. Kxh2 Kxg7 $11) 21... Qa6 22. Nf5 Be5 23. Bxe5 Rxe5 24. Nxg7 $5 Kxg7 25. Qg3+ Ng4 $1 {our key defensive resource.} 26. Qxg4+ Qg6 27. Qf3 {White still hopes for some small practical chances, but the engine kills everything:} Rae8 28. Qxb7 Qe4 $1 $11 {important move for clear equality.} *

