{[%evp 0,46,30,11,36,22,22,-1,44,45,45,45,41,44,44,44,44,36,28,31,45,48,72,51,57,42,49,37,37,34,20,29,41,45,46,36,43,45,51,27,36,39,39,35,31,12,10,-53,-83]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Ng3 {White's mainline, by far. 8.Ng3 has been played in around 50% of games that have reached this position.} Be7 $1 {the best development.} 9. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] very popular development.} O-O 10. Bb2 (10. c4 Bxf3 $1 11. Qxf3 c5 $1 $11 {Similar to 9.c4, but the inclusion of 00 and b3 makes things easier for Black.}) 10... b5 $5 {positional option, my favorite one.} (10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 c5 $5 $146 {we can play in the same style as after 9.c4, but it's a bit more risky here.} (11... c6 {standard move. You can play it and the position will be solid, but slightly worse for us, objectively.}) 12. d5 $5 {needs to be analyzed very well. 12.d5 looks as the critical move.} (12. Qxb7 cxd4 13. Rad1 Bc5 $132) 12... exd5 13. Rae1 Re8 14. Nh5 d4 $1 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. Qxb7 Ne5 $132 {You can debate if this position is equal or slightly better for White.}) 11. Ne5 {critical move.} (11. Qe2 Nd5 $132 (11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 b4 $132 {[%csl Gb4] also fine.})) (11. a3 Rb8 {[%csl Yb5][%cal Yc6a8,Yb8b5] we defend b5, and prepare Ba8-c5.} 12. Re1 Ba8 {[%cal Gc7c5] c5 is our idea.} 13. b4 {White stops c5, but we have many good ways:} Bd5 $5 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6] c6 next.} (13... a5 $5 {a bit more risky, but also works.} 14. bxa5 c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Bf1 Qxa5 17. Nf5 $1 exf5 18. Rxe7 Ne6 $11)) (11. c4 $6 {very common, but harmless and a bit dubious:} bxc4 12. bxc4 Rb8 $1 13. Rb1 Ba8 $36 {[%cal Gc7c5] c5 next, and the engine already prefers Black.}) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qd5 $1 $146 {key move. Very often, it will be our key resource after Nxe5-dxe5.} 13. f3 Qc5+ {For the engine, this position is critical, but there are no games.} 14. Rf2 {seems stronger, but who will understand it? In the future, White will have Raf1 coming faster.} (14. Kh1 Nd5 15. Bd4 $1 {key resource, otherwise White is worse.} Qa3 {[%cal Yd5f4]} 16. f4 f5 $1 {important move.} 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Bxf6 (18. Qg4 Rae8 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 $11) 18... Rxf6 19. Qe2 Qe7 $11 {[%csl Rf4]}) 14... Nd5 15. Bd4 $1 {once again, this is White's key resource, otherwise he is worse.} Qa3 16. f4 f5 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Bxf6 Rxf6 {I will share with you some engine lines for completeness, but it's highly unlikely that you will need them.} 19. Qh5 (19. Qe2 Qe7 20. Raf1 (20. Bxb5 Nxf4 21. Rxf4 Rxf4 22. Qe5 $1 Bxb5 23. Qxf4 $11) 20... Raf8 21. f5 (21. Qe4 g6 $11) 21... exf5 22. Nxf5 Qxe2 23. Rxe2 Bd7 $1 24. Ne7+ Nxe7 25. Rxf6 Rxf6 26. Rxe7 Rd6 $1 (26... Rf7 $2 27. Bxh7+ $1 $18) 27. Kf2 Kf8 28. Re5 a6 $11) 19... g6 20. Qe5 Qd6 $1 21. Qxd6 (21. Raf1 Qxe5 22. fxe5 Rxf2 23. Rxf2 Nc3 $132) 21... cxd6 22. Ne4 {Black has two ways for the draw:} Rxf4 (22... Rff8 23. Nxd6 Nc3 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga8d8] White has problems with the d6 knight.} 24. a4 a6 25. axb5 axb5 26. Re1 Rfd8 27. Ne4 Bxe4 28. Bxe4 Nxe4 29. Rxe4 {Black needs to be a bit precise in this endgame, for example:} Rd1+ 30. Rf1 Rd2 31. Rc1 Rf8 32. g3 Rf5 33. Rxe6 Rh5 34. h4 Rc5 $11) 23. c4 bxc4 24. bxc4 Rxf2 25. cxd5 Rxg2+ $1 26. Kxg2 Bxd5 $11 {piece for three pawns, this is just draw.} *

