{[%evp 0,30,28,16,30,36,36,33,44,31,45,45,36,54,51,47,47,40,28,26,31,31,40,37,38,33,42,46,40,49,46,49,50]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Ng3 Be7 9. Re1 {a standard move and also it's White's most common continuation.} O-O 10. c3 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yc3d4] In my opinion, this is White's best continuation. Not only it's a typical useful move, but it also prevents our Bxf3-Qxf3-c5 idea.} (10. Ne5 $2 {it's always important to check this move, but here it's not good:} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qd5 $1 {key resource; without it, our position would be much worse.} 12. Qf3 {White's best continuation, but it shows that Ne5 was wrong:} (12. f3 $2 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Ng4 $1 $17 {[%cal Gg4f2] White is in serious troubles.}) (12. Bf1 $2 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Ng4 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rf2][%cal Gg4e5,Gg4f2] White is in trouble to defend the weak e5 and f2 pawns.} 14. Re1 Bc5 15. Nh1 {only move.} f6 $1 $17 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf8f2] the rook joins the attack against f2.}) 12... Qxf3 13. gxf3 Nd5 $15 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Rf2,Rf3] We have a better endgame thanks to the active pieces and better structure.}) (10. c4 {very logical and intuitive move.} Bb4 $1 {strong concrete idea: White's rook doesn't have good squares.} 11. Rf1 {[%csl Rb4] sad move to play, but at least White deal with our concrete ideas, and the bishop on b4 is now misplaced.} (11. Bd2 $6 {no need to explain that this cannot be good:} Bxf3 $1 12. gxf3 Bxd2 13. Qxd2 c6 $15 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3]}) (11. Re3 Ng4 $1 {[%csl Re3] no comfortable moves for the rook.} 12. Re2 {sad necessity.} Bxf3 13. gxf3 Ngf6 $132 {strategically, we are doing great. It's only important to check} 14. Qb3 {[%csl Rb4] because it's a concrete move.} Bd6 15. c5 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Rc7c5] important move for White because it forces our bishop to retreat, and also it stops our c7-c5 idea.} (15. Qxb7 $6 {is not good because of} Bxg3 $1 16. hxg3 Nc5 $1 17. dxc5 Qxd3 $36 {White needs to work for the equality.}) 15... Be7 16. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5] only interesting plan for White, suggested by the engine. We need to think about f4-f5.} b6 {I like this positional move, after which the position gets balanced, for example:} 17. f5 bxc5 18. fxe6 Rb8 $1 {important move.} 19. exf7+ Rxf7 20. Qc2 {[%cal Gd3c4] White's threat is Bc4.} Kh8 {necessary.} 21. Bc4 Rf8 {it's easy for White to get worse over the board, but the engine finds:} 22. Bg5 $1 cxd4 23. Rd1 Nb6 $13 {and it's an unclear equal position.}) 11... Bd6 {[%cal Gc6f3,Yc7c5] We need to remove the bishop from b4. Our idea now is to play Bxf3 followed by c7-c5.} 12. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] engine's recommendation. Sometimes White will play with b4.} (12. b3 {most common move, and after} Bxf3 $1 13. Qxf3 c5 $1 $132 {our position is at least not worse.}) 12... a5 $5 $146 {[%cal Rb2b4,Gc6f3,Yd1f3,Yc7c5] We stop b4, and we renew the threart of Bxf3-Qxf3-c5.} (12... Bxf3 {still possible, but after} 13. Qxf3 c5 {you need to consider positional ideas like} 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 g6 16. b4 $5 {White is not better, but I prefer to radically stop b2-b4 ideas.})) (10. Qe2 {White wastes a tempo because after} Bxf3 $1 11. Qxf3 c5 $1 {we are fine, for example:} 12. dxc5 (12. Be3 Nd5 $5 $132 {[%csl Re3] the bishop on e3 is misplaced.}) (12. Qxb7 cxd4 $15 {[%csl Gd4] the exchange of b7 for d4 is always good for Black.}) 12... Nxc5 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Gc5d3]} 13. Bf1 {White saves the two bishops, but our pieces are very active and we are fine:} Qd5 {concrete option.} (13... Rc8 $5 {also good, just to play a game.}) 14. Qxd5 Nxd5 $132 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Yc5a4] Rfd8-Rac8-Na4. We have easy moves, and the engine already slightly prefers Black.}) 10... a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5a4] I like this move. We want to take space on the queenside.} (10... Bxf3 $6 {is not good now because after} 11. Qxf3 c5 {White can play} 12. Qxb7 $14 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Yc3d4] and the d4 pawn is defended.}) (10... b6 {is Black's most common move, but I am not a big fan of it:} 11. Bf4 $5 Bb7 12. Qe2 c5 {standard idea.} 13. Rad1 Qc8 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Bc2 $14 {White's pieces are well placed. We can still play after, for example, Qc6-Rfe8-Rad8, but White is sligthly better.}) 11. Qe2 {White has to complete the development.} (11. Bf4 {was White's move against 10..b6, so we need to check it also now.} a4 {[%csl Ga4] we continue taking space on the queenside.} 12. Qe2 {White plays in the style of 10...b6 11.Bf4 variation, and now our typical idea works:} Bxf3 (12... Bd6 $5 {is also good, and the position is equal.}) 13. Qxf3 c5 $1 14. Qxb7 Nd5 $1 $44 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gd5f4,Ga8b8,Ga4a3] We attack White's bishop and we can continue with Rb8 (if the bishop leaves f4) or with a3 to destroy White's structure. For sure we have full compensation.}) (11. a4 {looks logical, because White stops a5-a4, but now we can use the following idea:} Bd5 $5 {[%cal Gc7c5] we are ready for c5. The key point is that after} 12. c4 {which is always critical against the Bd5 idea, we can just play} Bc6 $132 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Ge7b4] and our bishop has achieved the ideal b4 square. Only after Bb4, we will probably go for the standard Bxf3-Qxf3-c5 idea.} 13. Bd2 {prevents Bb4 but allows} Nc5 $1 {[%csl Rd3] because the bishop on d3 is undefended.}) 11... a4 $146 {[%csl Ga4] It's a novelty, but it's also a very logical continuation of our previous move.} 12. a3 {this is how the engine plays with White. He just tries to slowly improve the position.} (12. Ne5 $2 {always better to check this move, but also here it doesn't work well:} Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qd5 $1 {key idea.} 14. Qf1 (14. f4 $2 Ng4 $1 $19 {[%csl Re1,Rf2]}) 14... Nd7 15. f4 Rfd8 $15) (12. Bd2 {after this normal looking move, we can go for} Bxf3 13. Qxf3 c5 $1 $11 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Yf3b7,Ga8b8,Gb8b2] because against Qxb7 we have Rb8-Rxb2 idea.}) 12... Re8 {we can also make useful moves, and the game is balanced. For example:} 13. Bc2 {the engine continues playing useful moves, and now I like the following idea:} (13. Bf4 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6f4] good move against Bf4.} 14. Ne5 {critical} Bxe5 $1 15. dxe5 Nd5 16. Bd2 Qh4 $11 {we have very good pieces.}) 13... Bd5 $5 {[%cal Gc7c5] e are ready for c5 next. If White plays} 14. c4 {which looks logical, we have an improved version of} Bxf3 15. Qxf3 c5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rc4] because White's pawn on c4 is worse than on c3. CONCLUSIONS: Although 9.Re1 is the most played move in the position, it is not dangerous for us. In the next chapter we will study 9.Qe2, which is more rare, but also more critical.} *

