{[%evp 0,42,24,38,39,39,33,1,50,50,55,50,55,49,49,49,48,31,31,36,59,78,63,56,69,56,59,41,78,47,54,29,47,46,41,44,50,40,44,41,32,38,37,52,51]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Ng3 Be7 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gf3e5] This move, in my opinion, is underrated. It might actually be the most challenging line against the Fort Knox Variation. With accurate play, however, Black can handle it.} Bxf3 $1 {This is the right moment to capture on f3. Yes, it's a small concession, but White had to spend a tempo (Qe2) to provoke it.} (9... O-O $6 {in the last chaper, we have seen that after 9.Re1, 9...00 works very well, but here the situation is different for concrete reasons:} 10. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qd5 (11... Nd7 {White has good chances for an advantage after many continuations:} 12. Nh5 $5 $40 (12. a4 $5)) 12. f4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge2,Yg2][%cal Ge2g2] big between the 9.Re1 and 9.Qg4 variations.}) 10. Qxf3 c6 {This is the only case in the entire database where we willingly play this structure with c6 in a middlegame, without the pair of bishops and with White still holding a knight. The key advantages in our favor are White's poorly placed knight on g3 and the tempo lost with Qe2 followed by Qxf3.} (10... c5 $6 {our standard idea doesn't work here:} 11. dxc5 $1 {and concretely we cannot equalize, for example:} Nxc5 (11... O-O 12. Ne4 $16) 12. Bb5+ $1 $16 {A key move that gives White the advantage. The Bxf3-Qxf3-c5 idea is rarely effective when we haven’t castled yet.}) (10... O-O $5 $146 {it's a possible alternative, but after} 11. Qxb7 c5 12. c3 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb6 $14 {We have some compensation, but I am not sure that it is full. According to the engine, the evaluation here is +0,40. You can make your own conclusions about it.}) 11. Re1 {This is the approach I find most concerning: White slowly improves his position with Re1 and c3, creating no clear targets. Unlike c4, which makes ...c5 more effective, or b3, which invites ...Qa5 and ...Ba3, Re1-c3 leaves Black uncertain about the best plan.} (11. c4 c5 $1 {We have transposed in Chapter 8 in the variation 9.c4 Bxf3 10.Qxf3 c5. Here, we have it at move 11 because White wasted a tempo for Qe2, and we wasted a tempo for c6.}) (11. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White's most common continuation, but I am not scared about it because we have now a clear idea:} Qa5 {[%cal Ge7a3] I like this move because we positionally prevent Bb2.} 12. a3 $1 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Re7a3] White prevents Ba3.} (12. Bb2 $6 {allows} Ba3 $1 {our position is already more than fine.} 13. Bxa3 Qxa3 14. Rfe1 O-O $11) 12... Qd5 {I like this move. We offer the queens exchange, and if White wants to avoid it, he should go to e3 or f4 to defend the d4 pawn.} (12... h5 $5 $146 {deserves attention.} 13. Ne2 $1 {The best, according to the engine. It's a prophylactic move against h4.} (13. Bb2 {natural move, but after it we have a good game.} h4 14. Ne2 (14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Rd8 16. c4 Nf6 17. Bc2 Qh5 $11 {very good for us.}) 14... g5 $5 15. c4 Qc7 $132 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gg5g4] 000 and g4 next. It's a new balanced position.}) 13... h4 (13... O-O $5 {Engine's move, and the evaluation is only +0,20. It looks a bit strange, yes, but maybe it works.} 14. Bb2 Rfe8 $14 {[%cal Ge7f8,Ge6e5] For now, it's slightly better for White, but if you analyze with the engine he just plays Bf8-e5 and equalizes with Black.}) 14. Qh3 Qh5 15. c4 g5 16. f4 g4 17. Qe3 $14 {Could be objectively slightly better for White, but of course over the board it's complicated.}) 13. Qe3 {White's best, and now it's a very important moment.} ({We are not worried about} 13. Qxd5 {because after} cxd5 $1 $11 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gd7b8,Gb8c6] the structure has changed, and here the two bishops are less important. Not to mention that b3-Bb2 is not a great development in this structure and Ng3 is bad. For example, we can continue with Nb8-Nc6 to improve our knight.}) (13. Qf4 {looks artificial, and we are fine after many moves:} Qd6 {maybe the simplest.} (13... h5 $5 $146 14. Ne2 (14. c4 Qd6 $1 $11 {[%cal Gd6f4] important tempo against White's queen.}) 14... e5 $11) 14. Qh4 (14. Qxd6 Bxd6 15. Bb2 O-O $11 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gf8e8,Ge6e5] Equal endgame. Ng3 is misplaced, and we have the very simple plan Re8-e5.}) 14... O-O $11 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gd7f8,Gf8g6] Rfd8-Nf8-Ng6 next.}) 13... c5 $1 {important move.} (13... h5 $6 {this was good against Qf4, but here we don't have Qd6 with tempo after} 14. c4 $1 Qd6 15. h3 $1 h4 16. Ne2 $16) ({If we just play} 13... O-O {then after} 14. c4 Qa5 15. Qf3 $14 {Nothing drammatic has happened, we are solid but White is definitely slightly better.}) 14. Ne2 $1 $146 {critical continuation: White improves the knight.} (14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Qe2 Qe5 16. Rb1 Qxe2 17. Bxe2 Rc8 $11 {Equal because our pieces are perfectly placed.} 18. c4 {only important thing is to prevent b4-c5 expansion.} b6 $1 $11 {We stop c4-c5 ideas.} (18... Ke7 $2 19. b4 Bd6 20. c5 $16 {this is better for White.})) (14. Bb2 cxd4 15. Qxd4 (15. Bxd4 Bc5 $1 $11 {important move to exchange the bishops.}) 15... Qxd4 16. Bxd4 O-O $11 {Full equality.}) 14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 Qe5 $1 {we are more afraid about the middlegame than about the endgame.} 16. Qxe5 Nxe5 17. Bb5+ Ned7 18. Bb2 O-O {This is probably the worst version of this typical endgame that we can get, but it's still very close to equal (+0,20, according to the engine). Let's try to make some engine's normal looking moves to understand what can happen:} 19. Rad1 Rfd8 20. Rfe1 Nc5 21. Bf1 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2] sometimes White wants g3-Bg2.} Ne8 $5 {[%cal Ge7f6] I like this plan to prepare Bf6.} (21... Rd6 {[%cal Ga8d8] also fine.}) (21... Kf8 {also fine.}) 22. g3 (22. Nf3 Rac8 23. g3 Bf6 $11 24. Ne5 Nd7 $1 $11) 22... Bf6 23. Bg2 Rd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8d8] no problem for Black.}) 11... O-O 12. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Ge1][%cal Yc1d2,Ya1d1] White is ready to continue with Bd2-Rad1, slowly improving his position.} a5 $5 {[%csl Ya5][%cal Ga5a4] This is my recommendation: when lacking a clear plan, the a5-a4 expansion is often an excellent solution.} 13. Bc2 $1 {[%csl Yc2] This is probably White's best move—it improves the position without creating any targets.} (13. Bd2 {this move allows a typical tactical idea:} c5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Yf3b7,Ga8b8,Gb8b2] not the only move, but I like it. The point is that after Qxb7-Rb8, White's b2 pawn will be hanging. That's the only drawback of the move Bd2.}) (13. a4 {now that White has played a4, we are more ready for} c5 $5 (13... Nd5 {is also fine. Our idea could be Bg5, that's why I think it's logical for White to play} 14. Ne4 {after which we can play another useful move like} Re8 $132 {[%cal Ge6e5] maybe we will be ready for e5 very soon. The game continues, but we are fine.}) 14. Qxb7 cxd4 15. cxd4 Nd5 $44 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Gd5b4,Ga8b8] we have the b4 square for our pieces, and this increases a lot our compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) (13. Bf4 {not a good square for White's bishop:} Nd5 $1 14. Bd2 {[%cal Gc3c4] White is ready for c4, but we are first:} Bg5 $1 $11 {after the exchange of the bishops, we have nothing to worry about.}) (13. Ne4 {is a move that we should welcome because the trade of the knights goes in our favor:} Nxe4 14. Qxe4 g6 $11 {[%cal Ge7g5,Ya5a4] we can continue with Bg5 if it will be possible, or with a5-a4.}) 13... a4 {[%cal Gd8a5,Gf8e8] we play another useful move, and maybe we will consider Qa5 on the next one.} (13... Qb6 $5 {[%cal Yc6c5] we stop White's Bc1 development, and somewhere we might be ready for c5.}) 14. a3 {the best, according to the engine, and now we can play} Qb6 $146 {[%csl Rc1] We stop the Bc1 development. Now, White has two options: the positional 15.Rb1, or the tactical 15.Nf5.} (14... Qa5 $6 {not so precise because of} 15. Bf4 $1 $14) 15. Nf5 $5 {critical from a concrete perspective.} (15. Rb1 {positional option. I suggest to continue improve our position with} Rfd8 {[%cal Gc6c5,Ye7f8] our Be7 will have available the f8 square, and very likely we can consider c6-c5 on the next move.} 16. Bg5 $1 {this move tactically prevents c5:} (16. Nf5 {too late for it:} Bf8 $11) (16. Bf4 c5 $132) (16. Be3 Qb5 $1 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] we are ready for c5 on the next move.}) 16... h6 {I’m not thrilled to play this move, as h6 could become a target later. However, the situation is concrete—it all comes down to whether we can achieve ...c5 under favorable conditions.} (16... c5 $2 17. d5 $1 {[%csl Gg5]} Nxd5 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Bxe7 Nxe7 $4 (19... Re8 20. Bg5 $16) 20. Qxf7 $18 {White is winning.}) 17. Be3 Qb5 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] we are ready for c5, and I was not able to find how White can stop it. The engine shows +0,20, but after we play c5 it slowly goes down to "0.00", which means that we have equalized.}) 15... exf5 $1 (15... Bd8 16. Ne3 $14 {White has improved his knight, while I don't like our bishop on d8.}) 16. Rxe7 Rfe8 {[%cal Ge8e1] we fight for the 'e' file.} 17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Ge8e1] Re1 is a major threat, and White cannot move the bishop from c1 without leaving b2 undefended.} 18. Qd1 {necessary move, and now we are just in time:} Qb5 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6] Nb6 next, and we are fine, for example:} 19. Qf1 {engine's try.} Nb6 $1 20. Qxb5 cxb5 21. Kf1 g6 $11 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Yb6c4,Yf6d5] White has the two bishops, but the queenside structure is locked, and our knights are ideally placed. We’ve not only equalized but also reached a position that’s comfortable to play. The 9.Qe2 variation may seem tricky at first, but with accurate analysis, it’s clear that Black has solid solutions. And here’s the good news: this line is rarely played, and even fewer players understand its potential for White. Unless you’re facing an exceptionally prepared opponent, it’s unlikely anyone will challenge you here. But after studying this chapter, you’ll be ready to handle even this worst scenario!} *

