{[%evp 0,38,19,38,43,18,28,33,67,42,53,32,39,51,50,50,46,15,23,15,24,24,26,28,27,26,25,22,21,30,28,-29,11,-3,-33,-30,-13,-21,-7,0,-9]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. Qe2 {[%cal Ye1c1,Ye4g5] White delays the short castle, and sometimes may consider the long castle or some ideas connected to Neg5.} Ngf6 8. Neg5 {This is White's most concrete and popular move.} (8. O-O {transposes in Chapter 2.}) (8. Ned2 Be7 (8... g6 $5 {is a good alternative here.}) 9. O-O O-O {transposes in Chapter 7.}) (8. Nxf6+ $5 {compared to chapter 7, 7.00 Ngf6 8.Nxf6, here we cannot take with the queen for concrete reasons.} Nxf6 (8... Qxf6 $2 9. Bg5 Bxf3 10. Qe3 $1 $18 {White's key move.}) 9. Bb5 $5 {was played against me by Ivan Salgado Lopez in the 2017 World Cup.} (9. O-O Bxf3 {easy solution.} (9... Be7 {is also playable.}) 10. Qxf3 Qd5 11. Qxd5 (11. Qd1 $5 $146 {maybe it's more interesting for White to keep the queens, and d1 is the best square according to the engine.} Be7 12. Be3 O-O 13. c4 Qa5 $132 {White has two bishops, but we are well-developed, and these positions are not dangerous if White doesn't have a knight.}) 11... Nxd5 $11 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] 000-g6-Bg7 next. It's an equal endgame.}) 9... Qd5 $1 {important move. 9...Qd7 was the same.} 10. Bxc6+ Qxc6 11. O-O Be7 {safer than Bd6. We are not worried about Ne5 ideas.} ({I have played} 11... Bd6 {but after} 12. Bg5 $14 {maybe White can pose a small pressure, like happened in the game Timman-Vaganian, 2008.}) 12. Ne5 (12. c4 Qe4 $11) (12. Bg5 O-O $11) 12... Qb6 $5 $146 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gc7c5] I like the queen on b6. Sometimes we can play c7-c5.} (12... Qd5 {has been played 5 times, but White will have c2-c4 tempo against our queen on d5.} 13. Be3 $132 {[%cal Gc2c4] still objectively fine, but I don't see a reason to play 12...Qd5.}) 13. c3 O-O 14. Be3 c5 $11) (8. Ng3 {We can continue with the typical idea} Bxf3 $1 9. Qxf3 c5 $1 {which was tried only once in the game Lobanov-Kacharava.} 10. dxc5 {critical move.} (10. Qxb7 cxd4 $132 {is good for us.}) 10... Bxc5 11. Ne4 $5 $146 {engine improvement over the mentioned game.} (11. Qxb7 $6 {risky for White.} Rb8 12. Qf3 Ne5 13. Qe2 {Lobanov-Kacharava, 2017.} Bb4+ $1 $146 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Rc1d2,Yb8b2] was very strong. White cannot play Bd2 because the b2 pawn will be hanging.} 14. Kf1 {only move.} Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Qc7 $36 {It's more than compensation: Black has the initiative.}) 11... Ne5 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Bb5+ Kf8 14. Qxf6 gxf6 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7] Ke7 next and we have a good endgame. In the start the engine shows +0,20, but after a few seconds it goes down to 0.00. From a human point of view, it looks absolutely fine for us.}) (8. Bd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] White plans 000. It's rare, but it makes sense.} Be7 9. O-O-O Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Bxe4 11. Qxe4 c6 $132 {[%cal Yd7f6,Yd8d5] typical playable Caro Kann style position. We can continue with Nf6-Qd5 next.}) 8... Qe7 {[%csl Re7,Rg5][%cal Ge8c8] I prefer Qe7 over h6 because we need to remember less forced variations. Our idea is to play 000. The queen on e7 looks strange with the bishop on f8, but White's knight on g5 is also misplaced.} (8... h6 $5 {is also possible, but more risky:} 9. Nxe6 fxe6 10. Bg6+ (10. Qxe6+ $2 Qe7 $19) 10... Ke7 {[%csl Re7] it might not be easy to play with the king on e7, but objectively the position is equal.} 11. O-O {the best.} (11. Nh4 $6 {[%cal Gh4f5] White's idea is Nf5 mate.} Nb6 12. O-O $1 $146 {only move for White.} (12. c4 $2 Kd7 $1 $17 {[%cal Gd7c8] Kc8 next and our position is winning.}) 12... Qd7 13. c4 Kd8 $15 {White has some compensation, but not full.}) (11. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] White prepares Ba3+.} Bxf3 $1 (11... Nb6 $2 {this was good against 11.Nh4, but not here because of} 12. Ne5 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge5]}) 12. Qxf3 (12. Ba3+ $4 c5 $19 {[%cal Gd8a5] Qa5+ next.}) 12... c5 13. O-O Qb6 $5 (13... Rc8 $15 {White doesn't have full compensation, but the position is still very unclear of course.}) 14. dxc5 Qc6 15. Qe2 a5 $1 $13 {[%cal Rb3b4] We prevent b4 and we can continue with Kd8 next.} (15... Kd8 $6 16. b4 $14)) 11... Bxf3 $1 {very important move; without it we are lost.} 12. Qxf3 Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gd8d5] also important. our idea is Qd5.} 13. Re1 (13. b3 Qd5 $13) (13. Qxb7 Rb8 14. Qf3 Qd5 $13) 13... Qd5 14. Qh3 Kd8 $1 15. Rxe6 Bd6 $13 {White has full compensation, but not more. It's a three results position.}) 9. O-O (9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 $36 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Ge8c8,Gd7c5,Yc5d3] 000 and Nc5 next. The engine already slightly prefers Black.}) (9. Bd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] White's idea is to play with 000.} h6 10. Ne4 O-O-O 11. O-O-O g5 $132 {[%cal Gf8g7] Bg7 next. Equal playable position.}) 9... h6 $1 {it's very important to play h6 right now.} (9... O-O-O $2 {would be a mistake because of} 10. b4 $1 h6 {and White can play} 11. b5 $1 Bd5 12. c4 hxg5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg5 $16) 10. Ne4 Bxe4 11. Bxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 O-O-O $132 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gf8g7] we want to play g5-Bg7 next. We have solved all the opening problems.} ({Let's follow the recent game Svidler-Rustemov.} 12... O-O-O 13. c4 {[%csl Rd4] I am not sure that c4 is the best plan for White, because now the d4 pawn will be vulnerable for all the rest of the game. Maybe 13.c3 was preferable.} g5 14. Re1 Bg7 15. b4 Rhe8 (15... Qxb4 {was also fine:} 16. Rb1 f5 $1 17. Qc2 Qd6 18. Qb3 Qb6 19. Rxe6 Qxb3 20. axb3 Rhe8 $36 {easier to play for Black, but objectively equal.}) 16. b5 f5 $1 17. Qc2 g4 18. Ne5 {and now it's an instructive moment. Rustemov played Nxe5, but I prefer} Bxe5 $5 19. dxe5 Nc5 $15 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gc5d3,Gh6h5,Gh5h4] our knight can go to d3. We can continue with h5-h4 next, and Black is slightly better.}) *

