{[%evp 0,26,16,19,36,33,20,-4,45,45,36,36,47,45,45,48,54,54,54,54,67,58,57,38,31,36,79,75,74]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 {In this last chapter about the Fort Knox variation, we will study White's remaining sidelines at move 7.} 7. c3 {tricky move.} (7. c4 {we already know that c4 is not always good for White:} Ngf6 8. Nc3 {and now, typical reaction:} Bxf3 $1 9. Qxf3 c5 $1 10. d5 {only critical move.} Ne5 11. Qe2 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 exd5 13. cxd5 Bd6 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8] 00 next, and it's at least equal.}) (7. Neg5 {doesn't make any sense because of} h6 $1 8. Ne4 {only move for White, and it shows that 7.Neg5 was not a great idea.} (8. Nxe6 $6 {doesn't work becase of} Qe7 $1 9. O-O fxe6 10. Bg6+ Kd8 $15) 8... Ngf6 $11 {We have one or two extra tempi compared to the mainlines.}) (7. Bf4 $5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gf4c7] GM Safarli has played it against me.} Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6 ({The idea of 7.Bf4 was that now we cannot recapture with the queen} 8... Qxf6 $2 9. Bxc7 $16) 9. O-O {the most precise way to equalize is} Bxf3 $1 10. Qxf3 c6 $132 {[%cal Gf8d6] Bd6 next. We have already discussed the fact that we are fine playing this structure against White's two bishops when one pair of knights has been exchanged.} 11. c3 (11. Be5 Nd7 $5 12. Bg3 Nf6 $11 {[%cal Gf8d6] Bd6 next.}) 11... Bd6 12. Be5 $5 {engine's move.} (12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Bc7 $5 $132 {[%cal Gd8d6] Qd6 next.}) 12... Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 $11 {no problem.}) 7... Ngf6 (7... h6 8. O-O Ngf6 9. Ned2 Be7 10. Qe2 b6 (10... O-O 11. Ne5) 11. Ne5) 8. Nxf6+ {Compared to Chapter 6 (same position but White played 00 instead of c3) now we cannot recapture with the queen for concrete reasons:} (8. Ng3 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 {transposes in Chapter 11.}) 8... Nxf6 (8... Qxf6 $4 9. Bg5 Bxf3 10. Qd2 $1 $18 {[%cal Rf6d4] White's pawn on d4 is protected.}) 9. O-O (9. Bf4 Nh5 $1 {the most precise move.} (9... Bd6 10. Ne5 $14) 10. Be3 (10. Be5 Bd6 11. O-O Nf4 $11) 10... Bd6 {[%cal Gh5f4] we are ready for Nf4.} 11. Ne5 {logical, but we are fine after} (11. O-O Nf4 $11) 11... Bxe5 12. Qxh5 (12. dxe5 $6 Qd5 $1 {forcing Qxh5.} 13. Qxh5 Qxd3 $15) 12... Bf6 $11) 9... Bxf3 $1 {the most precise way for equality.} 10. Qxf3 Qd5 11. Qg3 {White's most concrete continuation.} (11. Qxd5 Nxd5 $11 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Ge8c8] g6-Bg7-000 next, and we are very fine in this endgame.}) (11. Qe2 {most common continuation, but we can insist on the queens exchange offer:} Qh5 $1 12. Qc2 (12. Qxh5 Nxh5 $11) 12... Bd6 13. g3 O-O $11) (11. Qd1 {more precise than Qe2.} Bd6 (11... Qh5 $6 {is not good anymore because White has} 12. Be2 $1 $16) 12. Re1 {normal move.} c6 13. Qc2 O-O $132 {playable position. We are fine with it because White doesn't have knights.}) 11... Bd6 $1 12. Qh4 {and now we need to make the last precise move:} (12. Qg5 Qxg5 13. Bxg5 h6 $11 {endgames are fine for us.}) (12. Qxg7 $4 {is a huge blunder because of} Rg8 $1 $19 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gd5g2]}) 12... Qh5 $1 {White must exchange queens, and we can play a typical normal endgame.} 13. Qxh5 Nxh5 $11 ({let's follow two games played by GM Rustemov.} 13... Nxh5 14. f4 {I don't like this move.} (14. Be4 c6 15. f4 {once again, White plays this strange f2-f4 move.} (15. Bf3 Nf6 16. Rd1 O-O 17. Kf1 {is a normal way to play these positions. But Black is very solid and has nothing to worry about.} a5 $5 $132 {typical good move.}) 15... Nf6 16. Bf3 h5 $132 {[%cal Rg2g4] good move to prevent g2-g4 expantions. Black won in Jaiveer-Rustemov, 2023.}) 14... g6 $1 15. b4 {White wants to expant on all the sides of the board.} Nf6 16. b5 $6 {[%cal Gc7c5] allows c5 or c6 ideas.} O-O (16... c5 {was also good immediately.} 17. bxc6 bxc6 18. Rb1 O-O $132) 17. a4 c5 $1 {very strong move.} 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. Rb1 Rab8 20. Bd2 c5 $15 {Black was already preferable and won the game in Maltsevskaya-Rustemov, 2022.}) *

